@NODE "Installing amiCheck" "Installing amiCheck"
@TOC "Getting Started"

@{BG FILL}     @{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{I}Installing amiCheck @{UI}@{BG BACK}@{FG TEXT}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{BODY}
	amiCheck installation consists of two parts: installing the libraries and
then installing amiCheck itself.  The install script will ensure all
libraries required are installed into your LIBS: directory.  Then simply
drag the amiCheck drawer to the desired location. If you are upgrading,
drag your accounts into the new amiCheck drawer.  Thats it.

	Now try running amiCheck by double-clicking on the example.ac icon.  If
amiCheck does not come up with the example account, see the section on
@{"troubleshooting" LINK "Troubleshooting Installation"}. @{CODE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Configuring amiCheck" "Configuring amiCheck"
@TOC "Getting Started"

@{BG FILL}     @{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{I}Configuring amiCheck @{UI}@{BG BACK}@{FG TEXT}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{BODY}
	amiCheck is highly configurable, from fine details of the interface to
the number of transaction rows in the register window. The items below
detail how configurations will affect amiCheck.


@{FG SHINE}Tooltypes / command line parameters@{FG TEXT}

	amiCheck does not distinguish between CLI parameters or tooltypes,
therefore each of these may be listed on the command-line. For example,
"amiCheck USEMEMO myaccount.ac" is perfectly legal.  To install these as
tooltypes for workbench users, select the main amicheck icon, then select
the workbench menu item "icon/information".


	There are currently several tooltypes supported.  Tooltypes are a simple
way to configure the application by placing information into the
application's icon.  Click the amiCheck icon, and then select
"information..." under the icon menu item.   The icon information window
opens up, displaying the current amiCheck tooltypes. To comment out a
tooltype (have amiCheck ignore it), place "()"'s around it.  Likewise, to
uncomment it out, remove the "()"'s.


	@{B}"NUMROWS=xx"@{UB} provides the user with a method of setting the desired
number of transaction rows.  Note though that the rows requested is an
approximation.  NUMROWS=10 may give 8 or 9 rows.


	@{B}"AUTOSORT"@{UB}, if uncommented, maintains the sort preferences during the
session.  Reconciling, changing the filter, etc. will now re-assert the
sorting algorithm.  amiCheck will NOT re-sort after new data is entered or
an entry is modified.  This is so the user need not search the register to
verify the changes. To re-sort after modifications or new entries, use the
@{"sort" LINK "Using the Filter and Sort"} button.  If sorting is slow (you have a lot of visible entries), you
may want to permanently sort the database and turn off sorting.  This
tooltype is for those who do not wish to permanently affect the original
entered order of the transactions.


	@{B}"ASLHEIGHT=xx"@{UB} control the number of pixels high that pesky asl requester
is (I recommend 200!).


	@{B}"NUMCOLS=xx"@{UB} minimum number of columns for the main register.


	@{B}"TEMPLATEROWS=xx"@{UB} minimum number of rows in the template window menu
rearrangement


	@{B}"DCLICK=[CLEAR|EDIT|UNFILT]"@{UB} Default the double-click actions at startup
found in the preferences menus.


	@{B}"USEMEMO"@{UB} If present, defaults the two-line style register at startup as
found in the preferences menus.


	@{B}"DATE=[FORMAT1|FORMAT2|FORMAT3|FORMAT4]"@{UB} Default date format for the date
preferences (the order matches the list in the prefs/date menu: format 1 =
"12/31/99").


	@{B}"LOADPATTERN=#?.AC"@{UB} Customize the ASL load requester pattern field for
account files


	@{B}"SCRIPTPATTERN=#?.ACscript"@{UB} Customize the ASL load requester pattern
field for script files


	@{B}"NETPATTERN=#?.ACnet"@{UB} Customize the ASL load requester pattern field for
networth files


	@{B}"IMPORTPATTERN=#?.txt"@{UB} Customize the ASL load requester pattern field for
import files


	@{B}"NOLAYOUTWARN"@{UB}, if uncommented, removes the warning requester amiCheck
issues when it needs to modify the application layout in order to fit on
the workbench. NOLAYOUTWARN is initially commented out (the parentheses
surround comments) and must be uncommented in order to take effect. This
is a rather unnecessary feature, but Im keeping it.


@{FG SHINE}GUIFront Preferences@{FG TEXT}


	@{"GUIFront" LINK "About GUIFront"} by Michael Berg is an outstanding gadtools layout engine.  Berg
also provides the user with the means to configure the layout process on
an application by application basis.  For example, a user might desire the
popular "XEN" look, or to select a particular font other than the system
preferences font, or to select a particular screen for amiChecks to appear
on. There are many such options that should be looked into. See the
@{"GUIFront guide" LINK "GUIFront.guide/main" 0} for further information.


	If you do customise the screen preferences, you will want to select the
"Make Default" option in the guifront preferences screen window.  This
will make all programs launched by arexx use the amiCheck screen (such as
popping up the calculator).


@{FG SHINE}amiCheck Icons@{FG TEXT}


	In the amiCheck drawer is a second drawer, "AC_Icons". Here is where
amiCheck extracts common icons for reports, scripts, and accounts.  If the
user desires to create his or her own they must replace these. @{CODE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Troubleshooting Installation" "Troubleshooting Installation"
@TOC "Getting Started"

@{BG FILL}     @{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{I}Troubleshooting installation @{UI}@{BG BACK}@{FG TEXT}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{BODY}
@{FG SHINE}"amiCheck window never appears"@{FG TEXT}


	amiCheck requires v36 (OS2.04) or higher of AmigaDos.  If it cannot open
the proper libraries, it will immediately quit.  It will also quit if it
cannot find the GUIFront library in the libs: directory.


	If no font choice or window layout will allow amiCheck to fit on the
workbench, it will immediately quit.  HIRES NTSC with no overscan and
TOPAZ-8 is one of the smallest setups possible.


@{FG SHINE}"amiCheck shows a warning of layout changes"@{FG TEXT}


	amiCheck is warning that the appearance of the main window has been
altered (the application will not be affected).  To remove the requester,
see the discussion on Tooltypes, or perhaps try changing the screen font.
This is strictly an information requester, amiCheck as an application has
not been limited.


@{FG SHINE}"amiCheck doesn't use my font in some or all windows"@{FG TEXT}


	amiCheck selects the font on a window-by-window basis. Therefore it is
possible to have one window be able to use the user font, while others
"fall back" to default fonts in order to fit.


@{FG SHINE}"number of rows do not match the tooltype request"@{FG TEXT}


	The NUMROWS=xxx tooltype is only an approximation.  It will also be
clipped if the window is too tall to fit on the screen.

@{CODE}

@ENDNODE

